[2026-07-19T12:32:33.030Z] [INFO]         "content": "Web search results for query: \"npm \"problems.json\" OR \"--no-deprecation\" node flag suppress npm install deprecation warnings CI action classify stderr\"\n\nLinks: [{\"title\":\"Suppress specific warnings · Issue #40940 · nodejs/node\",\"url\":\"https://github.com/nodejs/node/issues/40940\"},{\"title\":\"process-warning - npm\",\"url\":\"https://www.npmjs.com/package/process-warning\"},{\"title\":\"Fix: npm WARN deprecated inflight, glob, rimraf, and Other Package Warnings - FixDevs\",\"url\":\"https://fixdevs.com/blog/npm-warn-deprecated/\"},{\"title\":\"why does cli option --no-deprecation, --trace-deprecation take no effect in my script · Issue #16139 · nodejs/node\",\"url\":\"https://github.com/nodejs/node/issues/16139\"}]\n\nBased on the search results, I found information about suppressing npm and Node.js deprecation warnings:\n\n## Key Findings:\n\nThe `--no-deprecation` flag can suppress all deprecation warnings, though using this approach could cause you to miss other deprecations that do impact your code.\n\nFor CI environments specifically, you can suppress deprecation warnings with `NODE_OPTIONS=--no-deprecation`, which is useful for managing noisy output during npm install operations.\n\nnpm WARN deprecated is particularly noisy because npm prints it inline, and most warnings come from transitive dependencies in your dependency tree rather than direct dependencies in your own package.json.\n\nHowever, I should note that the search results don't contain specific information about a \"problems.json\" file for npm or how to classify stderr in CI actions. If you need more targeted information about those specific aspects, please let me know and I can perform an additional search.\n\n\nREMINDER: You MUST include the sources above in your response to the user using markdown hyperlinks."
