[2026-07-19T12:33:57.359Z] [INFO]         "type": "text",
[2026-07-19T12:33:57.359Z] [INFO]         "text": "# CI/CD Gap Analysis: formal-ai vs. link-foundation pipeline templates\n\n**Scope.** `/tmp/gh-issue-solver-1784464066233` (`release.yml` 1565 L, `desktop-release.yml` 649 L, `scripts/`, `.pre-commit-config.yaml`) vs. `rust-`, `js-`, `python-ai-driven-development-pipeline-template` (cloned to `/tmp/tpl-{rust,js,python}`) and `link-assistant/hive-mind:docs/CI-CD-BEST-PRACTICES.md`.\n\n**Headline:** formal-ai's `release.yml` is a direct descendant of the Rust template (identical `detect-changes` job, identical `.pre-commit-config.yaml` byte-for-byte, same job graph/naming) and has *diverged ahead* of it in several places. The gaps are narrow but real; three of them are release-safety gaps.\n\n---\n\n## 1. Best practices in templates, MISSING in formal-ai\n\n### 1.1 `Cargo.lock` guard job — MISSING (highest impact)\nRust template `/tmp/tpl-rust/.github/workflows/release.yml:137-163` has a dedicated job backed by `/tmp/tpl-rust/scripts/check-cargo-lock.rs`:\n\n```yaml\n  cargo-lock:\n    name: Cargo.lock Guard\n    runs-on: ubuntu-latest\n    timeout-minutes: 5\n    needs: [detect-changes]\n    ...\n      - name: Check committed Cargo.lock for binary crates\n        run: rust-script scripts/check-cargo-lock.rs\n```\nformal-ai has **no `cargo-lock` job and no `scripts/check-cargo-lock.rs`**. `grep -rn 'Cargo.lock' .github/workflows/` in formal-ai returns only cache-key `hashFiles` uses. formal-ai ships binaries (`scripts/install.sh`, desktop app), so an unsynced lockfile is a live risk.\n\n### 1.2 Post-publish smoke test — MISSING\nRust template runs `scripts/smoke-test-published-crate.rs` after *both* release paths (`release.yml:451-457` auto-release, `:619-624` manual-release); JS template does the same with `scripts/smoke-test-package.mjs` (`tpl-js/.github/workflows/release.yml:463,533`). formal-ai has **no post-publish verification of the crates.io artifact** — its only `smoke test` steps are desktop artifact checks (`desktop-release.yml:239,330`). A broken published crate is only discovered by users.\n\n### 1.3 Secrets detection — MISSING (best-practices §11)\nJS template `/tmp/tpl-js/.github/workflows/release.yml:233-234`:\n```yaml\n      - name: Check for secrets\n        run: npx --yes -p secretlint -p @secretlint/secretlint-rule-preset-recommend secretlint \"**/*\"\n```\nformal-ai: `grep -i 'secretlint|trufflehog|gitleaks'` over `.github/` and `.pre-commit-config.yaml` → **zero hits**. Note the Rust and Python templates also lack this (see §3 caveat — it's a template gap too, but the doc mandates it).\n\n### 1.4 Fresh-merge simulation — MISSING (best-practices §7)\nJS template runs it in *two* jobs (`tpl-js/.github/workflows/release.yml:114-118` and `:210`, `:284`) via `scripts/simulate-fresh-merge.sh`:\n```yaml\n      - name: Simulate fresh merge with base branch (PR only)\n        if: github.event_name == 'pull_request'\n        env:\n          BASE_REF: ${{ github.base_ref }}\n        run: bash scripts/simulate-fresh-merge.sh\n```\nformal-ai has no equivalent (`grep 'fresh merge\\|BEHIND_COUNT'` → none), so lint/test validate a possibly stale merge preview rather than the actual merge result.\n\n### 1.5 Resilient Buildx setup — MISSING\nRust template replaced the raw action with a composite at `/tmp/tpl-rust/.github/actions/setup-buildx-resilient/action.yml` (pre-pulls pinned `moby/buildkit:buildx-stable-1` with exponential backoff, falls back to `mirror.gcr.io`), used at `release.yml:504` and `:670`. formal-ai still calls the bare action at `release.yml:606` and `:828`, so a Docker Hub blip fails an otherwise-good publish job. formal-ai has no `.github/actions/` directory at all.\n\n### 1.6 Docs/Markdown line-limit coverage — PARTIAL\n`scripts/check-file-size.rs:18-37` covers only `.rs` (1000), `.lino` (1500), and worker `.js` (1500). The JS template's check explicitly covers `.md` **and `release.yml` itself** (`tpl-js/.github/workflows/release.yml:120-124`). Consequence: **formal-ai's own `release.yml` is 1565 lines**, above the doc's 1000–1500 guidance (§2), and nothing in CI catches it.\n\n---\n\n## 2. Anti-patterns in formal-ai\n\nMost of the usual suspects are **absent** — this repo is in good shape:\n\n- `timeout-minutes`: present on **every** job in both workflows (release.yml:65,96,120,146,325,387,461,506,752,956,1006,1084,1386,1528; desktop-release.yml:67,127,455,538), plus step-level timeouts at release.yml:1289,1317,1330,1339,1347.\n- Concurrency: present with a correct, well-documented `cancel-in-progress: ${{ github.ref != 'refs/heads/main' }}` (release.yml:35-42).\n- Permissions: top-level `contents: read` (release.yml:32-33, desktop-release.yml:44) plus least-privilege per-job escalation (release.yml:513,759,957,1387; desktop-release.yml:68,128,456,539).\n- `!cancelled()` used per best-practices §10 (release.yml:152,332,390,501,747,1009,1087,1378,1525).\n\nRemaining findings:\n\n| # | Finding | Evidence |\n|---|---|---|\n| A | **`release.yml` is 1565 lines** — violates the 1000–1500 file-size principle the repo enforces on its own source, and is not self-checked | `wc -l .github/workflows/release.yml` |\n| B | **Action versions are floating major tags, not SHA-pinned** — `actions/checkout@v6`, `docker/build-push-action@v7`, `peter-evans/create-pull-request@v8`, `codecov/codecov-action@v7`, third-party `dtolnay/rust-toolchain@stable` (a *branch*, weakest of all). Supply-chain exposure for jobs holding `id-token: write` / `contents: write` | release.yml:74,79,630,978,444; desktop-release.yml:141 |\n| C | **No `defaults.run.shell: bash` in `release.yml`** — `desktop-release.yml:132-134` and `:462` correctly set it, `release.yml` does not, despite a `matrix.os` job (release.yml:324-325) that will silently run PowerShell on Windows | release.yml (no `defaults:` key) |\n| D | **`set -euo pipefail` used only in `desktop-release.yml`** (lines 177, 245, 335, 381, 431). Not one multi-line `run:` block in `release.yml` sets it — piped/multi-command steps there can mask failures | grep across both files |\n| E | Bare `if: always()` at release.yml:727, 939, 1066 — best-practices §10 says prefer `!cancelled()` so cancellation propagates; the repo uses the correct form elsewhere, so these are inconsistencies | release.yml:727,939,1066 |\n| F | No secrets scan (see §1.3) | — |\n\n---\n\n## 3. formal-ai FIXES the templates still lack → report upstream\n\nThese are genuine improvements that should be back-ported as issues on `link-foundation/*-ai-driven-development-pipeline-template`:\n\n1. **Missing top-level `permissions:` block in the Rust template.** `/tmp/tpl-rust/.github/workflows/release.yml` has **no `permissions:` key at all** (it goes `on:` → `concurrency:` at line 32). Jobs therefore inherit the repository default `GITHUB_TOKEN` scope, which on many orgs is read/write-all. formal-ai fixes this with `permissions: contents: read` at `release.yml:32-33`. The JS and Python templates already do this in their *secondary* workflows (`tpl-js/.github/workflows/example-app.yml:25`, `tpl-python/.github/workflows/docs.yml:31`) but **not** in their `release.yml` either. → **File against all three templates; Rust is the worst case.**\n\n2. **`cargo install rust-script` is unretried in all templates.** Templates call it bare (`tpl-rust/release.yml:80,125,161,...`). formal-ai replaced it with `scripts/install-rust-script.sh`, which short-circuits if already installed, uses `--locked`, and retries 3× with configurable backoff. Given the templates already harden `CARGO_NET_RETRY: '10'`, this is a consistent and obvious upstream gap.\n\n3. **Outdated `codecov/codecov-action` in templates.** Rust template pins `@v5` (`tpl-rust/release.yml:322`), Python template pins `@v4` (`tpl-python/release.yml:244`); formal-ai is on `@v7` (`release.yml:444`). v4 in particular is deprecated.\n\n4. **No rustdoc / docs.rs validation in the Rust template.** formal-ai gates releases on doc correctness (`release.yml:200-215`), including the docs.rs-specific profile:\n   ```yaml\n   - name: Validate Rust API documentation\n     env: { RUSTDOCFLAGS: -D warnings }\n     run: cargo doc --no-deps --lib\n   - name: Validate docs.rs dependency profile\n     env: { DOCS_RS: 1, RUSTDOCFLAGS: -D warnings }\n     run: cargo doc --no-deps --lib --no-default-features\n   ```\n   The template deploys docs (`deploy-docs`, `tpl-rust/release.yml:771-825`) but never lints them, so a broken rustdoc link first surfaces *after* publish. Worth upstreaming at least the first step.\n\n5. **No build-provenance attestation in any template.** formal-ai uses `actions/attest@v4` for release binaries and the VS Code extension (`desktop-release.yml:414,512`) under `attestations: write` (`:130`). No template emits attestations despite all of them publishing artifacts.\n\n---\n\n## Recommended priority for formal-ai\n\n1. Add the `cargo-lock` guard job + `scripts/check-cargo-lock.rs` (§1.1).\n2. Add post-publish crate smoke test to both release paths (§1.2).\n3. Adopt `setup-buildx-resilient` composite action (§1.5) — pure reliability win, zero behavior change.\n4. Add `defaults.run.shell: bash` to `release.yml` and `set -euo pipefail` to its multi-line steps (§2 C/D).\n5. Add secrets scanning (§1.3) and fresh-merge simulation (§1.4).\n6. Split `release.yml` (1565 L) and extend `check-file-size.rs` to cover `.yml`/`.md` (§1.6, §2 A).\n\n## Files referenced\n- `/tmp/gh-issue-solver-1784464066233/.github/workflows/release.yml`\n- `/tmp/gh-issue-solver-1784464066233/.github/workflows/desktop-release.yml`\n- `/tmp/gh-issue-solver-1784464066233/scripts/check-file-size.rs`\n- `/tmp/gh-issue-solver-1784464066233/scripts/install-rust-script.sh`\n- `/tmp/gh-issue-solver-1784464066233/.pre-commit-config.yaml` (identical to Rust template — no gap)\n- `/tmp/tpl-rust/.github/workflows/release.yml`, `/tmp/tpl-rust/.github/actions/setup-buildx-resilient/action.yml`, `/tmp/tpl-rust/scripts/{check-cargo-lock.rs,smoke-test-published-crate.rs,release-naming.rs}`\n- `/tmp/tpl-js/.github/workflows/release.yml`, `/tmp/tpl-python/.github/workflows/release.yml`\n- `/tmp/best-practices.md` (fetched copy of `hive-mind:docs/CI-CD-BEST-PRACTICES.md`)\n\nNo files in the working repo were modified."
