[2026-07-19T12:36:35.529Z] [INFO]     "model": "claude-opus-4-8",
[2026-07-19T12:36:35.529Z] [INFO]     "id": "msg_011CdBRfYBYoXDHqq1tHvTdk",
[2026-07-19T12:36:35.529Z] [INFO]     "type": "message",
[2026-07-19T12:36:35.529Z] [INFO]     "role": "assistant",
[2026-07-19T12:36:35.529Z] [INFO]     "content": [
[2026-07-19T12:36:35.529Z] [INFO]       {
[2026-07-19T12:36:35.529Z] [INFO]         "type": "text",
[2026-07-19T12:36:35.529Z] [INFO]         "text": "## 1. npm deprecation warnings in CI\n\n**Nature of the signal.** `npm warn deprecated ...` goes to **stderr** but is not an error — npm exits 0. Anything in CI that treats non-empty stderr as failure will break on it. npm's own knob is `loglevel`, whose values are `silent, error, warn, notice (default), http, info, verbose, silly` ([npm config docs](https://docs.npmjs.com/cli/v11/using-npm/config#loglevel)). `npm ci --loglevel=error` (or `--silent`/`-s`) suppresses deprecation lines. Full output is still written to the debug log under `~/.npm/_logs/`, so nothing is lost.\n\n**Granularity does not exist.** npm warns about every deprecated package anywhere in the tree, with no per-package or transitive-only suppression. This is an open, unresolved request: [npm/cli#7633 \"Make deprecation notices less scary\"](https://github.com/npm/cli/issues/7633). pnpm has the same gap ([pnpm#9720](https://github.com/pnpm/pnpm/issues/9720), [pnpm#4306](https://github.com/pnpm/pnpm/issues/4306)); note pnpm's `loglevel=error` reportedly does *not* suppress them ([pnpm#4343](https://github.com/pnpm/pnpm/issues/4343)). So the choice is all-or-nothing.\n\n**`--no-deprecation` is the wrong tool.** That's a **Node** flag (`NODE_OPTIONS=--no-deprecation`) suppressing `process.emitWarning` DeprecationWarnings at runtime; it does not affect npm's registry-metadata `npm warn deprecated` lines. Related: [nodejs/node#40940](https://github.com/nodejs/node/issues/40940), [nodejs/node#16139](https://github.com/nodejs/node/issues/16139).\n\n**Is there an existing classifier for npm stderr diagnostics?** I found none — no library, npm package, or GitHub Action that parses/classifies `npm warn` lines by category. There is also **no `problems.json` in npm**; that filename does not correspond to any npm feature. The closest existing primitives:\n- `npm audit --json` (vulnerabilities only, not deprecations)\n- `npm ls --json` / `npm query \"*\"` — I verified against npm's real output that **neither exposes a `deprecated` field**; available keys are `version, resolved, integrity, dev, license, name, _id, pkgid, location, path, realpath, from, to, inBundle, deduped, overridden, queryContext`. `npm query \":deprecated\"` errors with `EQUERYNOPSEUDO`.\n- So programmatic classification requires either regex over stderr (`^npm warn deprecated (\\S+)@(\\S+): (.*)$`) or a registry lookup per resolved version (`npm view pkg@ver deprecated`).\n\n**Recommended CI shape:** run install with `--loglevel=error` so the build isn't broken by benign stderr, and handle deprecation *policy* separately and asynchronously (Dependabot/Renovate/Snyk), rather than gating the build on stderr emptiness.\n\n**glob@10.5.0 — yes, this is real and recent.** glob deprecated everything except 12.x/13.x. Message text: *\"Old versions of glob are not supported, and contain widely publicized security vulnerabilities, which have been fixed in the current version. Please update. Support for old versions may be purchased (at exorbitant rates) by contacting i@izs.me\"*. The wrinkle: **10.5.0 and 11.1.0 are themselves the patch releases for CVE-2025-64756 yet are still flagged deprecated**, which is exactly the confusion filed as [isaacs/node-glob#644](https://github.com/isaacs/node-glob/issues/644). Downstream fallout is widespread: [mochajs/mocha#5779](https://github.com/mochajs/mocha/issues/5779), [jestjs/jest#15910](https://github.com/jestjs/jest/issues/15910), [google-gemini/gemini-cli#18327](https://github.com/google-gemini/gemini-cli/issues/18327), [microsoft/vscode#267530](https://github.com/microsoft/vscode/issues/267530). So the warning is unavoidable noise, not an actionable vulnerability.\n\n**Important correction on the dependency chain — it is NOT vsce or electron-builder.** I resolved this against the committed lockfiles rather than assuming:\n\n- `@vscode/vsce@3.9.2` already depends on `glob ^13.0.6` — clean.\n- electron-builder pulls only `glob@7.2.3` (via `@electron/asar` and `rimraf`) — a different, older warning.\n- The actual `glob@10.5.0` in both `/tmp/gh-issue-solver-1784464066233/vscode/package-lock.json` (line 1592) and `/tmp/gh-issue-solver-1784464066233/desktop/package-lock.json` (line 3612) comes from your **own first-party package**:\n\n  `@link-assistant/web-capture` → `archiver@^7.0.1` → `archiver-utils@^5.0.2` → `glob ^10.0.0` → resolves to `10.5.0`\n\nThat means this one is fixable at source rather than only suppressible: bumping `archiver` (or overriding `glob` to 13.x) in `@link-assistant/web-capture` clears it in both workspaces. Worth doing before reaching for blanket stderr suppression.\n\n## 2. Git trailers\n\n**Confirmed authoritatively.** From [git-interpret-trailers docs](https://git-scm.com/docs/git-interpret-trailers), verbatim:\n\n> \"Existing trailers are extracted from the input by looking for a group of one or more lines that (i) is all trailers, or (ii) contains at least one Git-generated or user-configured trailer and consists of at least 25% trailers. The group must be preceded by one or more empty (or whitespace-only) lines. The group must either be at the end of the input or be the last non-whitespace lines before a line that starts with `---`.\"\n\nThis confirms the premise exactly: only **one** group is recognized, it must be **at the end of the input**, and it must be preceded by a blank line. A blank line between two trailers splits them into two paragraphs, and only the final paragraph is the trailer block — the earlier trailer becomes invisible to both `git interpret-trailers` and `%(trailers)` in `git log --format`. The 25% heuristic adds a second failure mode: a trailer-looking line adjacent to enough prose can be swallowed.\n\n**`--no-divider` does not help here.** It means \"treat `---` as end of commit message\" and is already the default; it's about `git format-patch`/email input, not about multi-paragraph trailer blocks. There is no option to make git scan earlier paragraphs.\n\n**Robust validation approach.** Use `git interpret-trailers --parse` (a documented alias for `--only-trailers --only-input --unfold`) — `--only-input` prevents configured/`trailer.*` additions from contaminating results, and `--unfold` collapses folded multi-line values into one line, making the output machine-parseable. Equivalently `git log -1 --format='%(trailers:only=true,unfold=true)'`. Validate by comparing the parsed set against expectations; critically, also **detect the failure mode** by scanning the raw message for trailer-shaped lines (`^[A-Za-z][A-Za-z0-9-]*: `) that do *not* appear in the parsed output — that difference is precisely the \"orphaned trailer above a blank line\" bug, and it's the check neither git nor off-the-shelf linters give you.\n\n**Existing tools — limited reuse.** commitlint has a built-in `signed-off-by` rule plus `footer-*` rules ([rules reference](https://commitlint.js.org/reference/rules.html)), and a `trailer-exists` rule appears in docs but is [not actually recognized as a valid rule name](https://github.com/conventional-changelog/commitlint/issues/3033). Its footer handling is its own conventional-commits parser, not git's trailer algorithm, so it will happily accept a message git itself parses differently — meaning it cannot catch the blank-line bug. [Conventional Commits](https://www.conventionalcommits.org/en/v1.0.0/) explicitly models footers on the git trailer convention but likewise defines its own parse. Bottom line: no existing linter validates against git's *actual* last-paragraph semantics; a thin wrapper over `git interpret-trailers --parse` is the trustworthy option, since it's the same code path any consumer will use.\n\nSources: [git-interpret-trailers](https://git-scm.com/docs/git-interpret-trailers) · [npm config](https://docs.npmjs.com/cli/v11/using-npm/config#loglevel) · [npm/cli#7633](https://github.com/npm/cli/issues/7633) · [pnpm#9720](https://github.com/pnpm/pnpm/issues/9720) · [pnpm#4343](https://github.com/pnpm/pnpm/issues/4343) · [nodejs/node#40940](https://github.com/nodejs/node/issues/40940) · [isaacs/node-glob#644](https://github.com/isaacs/node-glob/issues/644) · [mochajs/mocha#5779](https://github.com/mochajs/mocha/issues/5779) · [jestjs/jest#15910](https://github.com/jestjs/jest/issues/15910) · [gemini-cli#18327](https://github.com/google-gemini/gemini-cli/issues/18327) · [microsoft/vscode#267530](https://github.com/microsoft/vscode/issues/267530) · [commitlint rules](https://commitlint.js.org/reference/rules.html) · [commitlint#3033](https://github.com/conventional-changelog/commitlint/issues/3033) · [Conventional Commits](https://www.conventionalcommits.org/en/v1.0.0/) · [Microsoft: npm warnings advice](https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/office/dev/add-ins/overview/npm-warnings-advice)"
