[2026-07-19T12:55:27.614Z] [INFO] {
[2026-07-19T12:55:27.614Z] [INFO]   "type": "assistant",
[2026-07-19T12:55:27.614Z] [INFO]   "message": {
[2026-07-19T12:55:27.614Z] [INFO]     "model": "claude-opus-4-8",
[2026-07-19T12:55:27.614Z] [INFO]     "id": "msg_011CdBT8r8RYwqkmAgJZvs18",
[2026-07-19T12:55:27.614Z] [INFO]     "type": "message",
[2026-07-19T12:55:27.614Z] [INFO]     "role": "assistant",
[2026-07-19T12:55:27.614Z] [INFO]     "content": [
[2026-07-19T12:55:27.614Z] [INFO]       {
[2026-07-19T12:55:27.614Z] [INFO]         "type": "tool_use",
[2026-07-19T12:55:27.614Z] [INFO]         "id": "toolu_011oqdKAABMDzpN1cGicqmHq",
[2026-07-19T12:55:27.614Z] [INFO]         "name": "Bash",
[2026-07-19T12:55:27.614Z] [INFO]         "input": {
[2026-07-19T12:55:27.614Z] [INFO]           "command": "cd /tmp && gh issue create --repo link-assistant/web-capture --title \"archiver@7 pulls deprecated glob@10.5.0 into every consumer; archiver@8 removes it\" --body \"$(cat <<'EOF'\n## Summary\n\n`js/package.json` depends on `archiver: ^7.0.1`, which pulls a deprecated `glob` into every downstream consumer:\n\n```\n@link-assistant/web-capture@1.10.10\n  -> archiver@7.0.1\n    -> archiver-utils@5.0.2   (declares glob ^10.0.0)\n      -> glob@10.5.0          <-- deprecated\n```\n\n`archiver-utils` has not been released since 5.0.2 and still declares `glob ^10.0.0`, so this cannot be resolved by a lockfile refresh.\n\n## Impact\n\nUpstream deprecated **every** `glob` below 12.x — including `10.5.0` and `11.1.0`, which are themselves the patch releases for CVE-2025-64756 (see [isaacs/node-glob#644](https://github.com/isaacs/node-glob/issues/644)). Every `npm install` in a consuming project therefore emits:\n\n```\nnpm warn deprecated glob@10.5.0: Old versions of glob are not supported, please upgrade to glob v12 or later\n```\n\nnpm writes this to stderr while still exiting 0, and it cannot be filtered per-package ([npm/cli#7633](https://github.com/npm/cli/issues/7633)). In `link-assistant/formal-ai` this failed the `.vsix` packaging job and all four desktop builds, because the CI stderr check treated the unrecognised warning as a real diagnostic (link-assistant/formal-ai#796).\n\n## Reproducible example\n\n```bash\nmkdir /tmp/repro && cd /tmp/repro\nnpm init -y >/dev/null\nnpm install @link-assistant/web-capture@1.10.10 --no-audit --no-fund 2>&1 | grep 'deprecated glob'\n# npm warn deprecated glob@10.5.0: Old versions of glob are not supported...\n\nnpm ls glob\n# ... archiver@7.0.1 -> archiver-utils@5.0.2 -> glob@10.5.0\n```\n\n## Suggested fix\n\n**Bump to `archiver@^8.0.0`.** Verified against the registry: archiver 8.0.0 drops the `archiver-utils` dependency entirely and replaces the glob-based walker with `readdir-glob@^3`, which depends only on `minimatch@^10`. There is no `glob` anywhere in its tree.\n\n```diff\n-    \"archiver\": \"^7.0.1\",\n+    \"archiver\": \"^8.0.0\",\n```\n\n`archiver@8` requires `node >= 18`. Please check that against this package's supported range before merging; if Node 16 must still be supported, use the workaround below instead.\n\n## Workaround for consumers\n\nUntil this lands, consumers can force the resolution themselves:\n\n```json\n{ \"overrides\": { \"glob\": \"^13.0.0\" } }\n```\n\nThis is what `@vscode/vsce@3.9.2` already does natively (it depends on `glob ^13.0.6`). Consumers whose CI treats npm stderr as fatal can also allowlist the warning by package name rather than by exact `name@version` — pinning the version breaks the moment a transitive dependency floats to a new patch, which is exactly how the formal-ai failure occurred.\nEOF\n)\"",
