[2026-07-19T12:56:09.250Z] [INFO] {
[2026-07-19T12:56:09.250Z] [INFO]   "type": "assistant",
[2026-07-19T12:56:09.250Z] [INFO]   "message": {
[2026-07-19T12:56:09.250Z] [INFO]     "model": "claude-opus-4-8",
[2026-07-19T12:56:09.250Z] [INFO]     "id": "msg_011CdBTC4rydP3B2YFYyNmoi",
[2026-07-19T12:56:09.250Z] [INFO]     "type": "message",
[2026-07-19T12:56:09.250Z] [INFO]     "role": "assistant",
[2026-07-19T12:56:09.250Z] [INFO]     "content": [
[2026-07-19T12:56:09.250Z] [INFO]       {
[2026-07-19T12:56:09.250Z] [INFO]         "type": "tool_use",
[2026-07-19T12:56:09.250Z] [INFO]         "id": "toolu_01UueYwy92d9nPujFvzzR3et",
[2026-07-19T12:56:09.250Z] [INFO]         "name": "Bash",
[2026-07-19T12:56:09.250Z] [INFO]         "input": {
[2026-07-19T12:56:09.250Z] [INFO]           "command": "cd /tmp && gh issue create --repo link-foundation/rust-ai-driven-development-pipeline-template --title \"cargo install rust-script is unretried and unlocked at three sites; a registry blip fails the release\" --body \"$(cat <<'EOF'\n## Summary\n\n`release.yml` runs bare `cargo install rust-script` at three sites (lines 76, 101, 124). Each is a single unretried network operation, and none passes `--locked`.\n\nThis is inconsistent with the workflow's own posture: it already sets `CARGO_NET_RETRY: '10'`, which covers cargo's *registry* fetches but **not** the resolution and build of the installed binary. A crates.io blip during any of those three steps fails an otherwise-good release.\n\nTwo secondary problems:\n\n1. **No `--locked`.** `cargo install` resolves dependencies fresh, ignoring the published `Cargo.lock`. A broken transitive release breaks the pipeline with no change on your side, and builds are not reproducible.\n2. **No short-circuit.** The binary is compiled from source on every run of every job, even when a cached or preinstalled copy is present.\n\n## Reproducible example\n\nSimulate a transient registry failure:\n\n```bash\n# any network interruption during this step fails the whole job\ncargo install rust-script\n# error: failed to download from https://crates.io/api/v1/crates/...\n# Caused by: [28] Timeout was reached\necho $?   # -> 101, job fails, no retry\n```\n\n## Suggested fix\n\nReplace the three call sites with a script that short-circuits, locks, and retries with backoff:\n\n```bash\n#!/usr/bin/env bash\nset -euo pipefail\n\nif command -v rust-script >/dev/null 2>&1; then\n  echo \"rust-script already present: $(rust-script --version)\"\n  exit 0\nfi\n\nfor attempt in 1 2 3; do\n  if cargo install rust-script --locked; then\n    exit 0\n  fi\n  echo \"cargo install rust-script failed (attempt $attempt/3); retrying...\" >&2\n  sleep $((attempt * 5))\ndone\n\necho \"cargo install rust-script failed after 3 attempts\" >&2\nexit 1\n```\n\nand call it as `- run: ./scripts/install-rust-script.sh` at each of the three sites. `link-assistant/formal-ai` runs this exact approach in production (`scripts/install-rust-script.sh`).\n\n## Workaround\n\nConsumers of the template can add `--locked` and wrap the step in a retry loop inline, or use `taiki-e/install-action` / `cargo-binstall` to fetch a prebuilt binary instead of compiling. The script above is preferred for the template because it has no third-party action dependency.\n\n## Scope\n\nRust template only — verified that the `js-` and `python-` templates do not invoke `cargo install rust-script`. Found while auditing CI/CD against these templates in link-assistant/formal-ai#796.\nEOF\n)\"",
[2026-07-19T12:56:09.250Z] [INFO]           "description": "File rust-script retry issue"
[2026-07-19T12:56:09.250Z] [INFO]         },
